text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: AAVE discrimination in the Judicial system%0a:Author: BrandtE%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 24.04.2021 - 19:44%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-222633-338350#%0a* [-11.05.2021 - 15:26-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-222633-338350#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-222622-146030#%0a----%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-11.05.2021 - 15:26-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a!!!!!TA_mason%0aThanks Brandt, interesting article! %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210511-222622-146030 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a#foxend 210511-222622-146030#%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aIn this article, I discuss an article about discrimination against AAVE in the judicial system.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI'm linking to an article from a Stanford linguist about discrimination in the judicial system against AAVE%0a%0ahttps://news.stanford.edu/news/2014/december/vernacular-trial-testimony-120214.html%0a%0aIn the article it takes a particularly close look at the George Zimmerman trial and the testimony from the prosecution's witness Rachel Jeantel. The article discusses how Rachel's use of AAVE (African American Vernacular English), leads her to be misunderstood and even prejudged. Situations like this one are of particular importance because of the stakes, if testimony is not understood or discredited due to a speakers use of a dialect it could mean justice isn't done or someone is wrongfully convicted. In the case of Rachel Jeantel, there are a variety of examples where Rachel uses AAVE which would be understood as ungrammatical in SAE.%0a%0aRachel uses stressed BIN: "I was been paying attention, sir". She uses preterit tense had as well as consonant metathesis in ask: "He had ask me did I go to the hospital" where ask is pronounced [æks]. She also drops copula: "He by the area where his daddy fiancée house is." where an 'is' would be included before by in SAE.%0a%0aThe article charges that because none of the jurors were African American and presumably weren't AAVE speakers, they could very well misunderstand or judge Rachel's character and by extension her testimony by the way she spoke.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
